As @HomeworkHopper was implying, if you are using Java 16 or newer, the standard solution is to use a [`Java Record`][1]. (that link is for the latest version, Java 20 -- strive to use the latest version when possible)

You can then do something like this.

```java
    class Response {final int id; /* constructors and stuff here. */}
    
    record BundledResponse (Response response, SomeOtherData etc) {}
```

Which enables you to do something like this. I have added types to properly communicate what is happening.

```java
CompletableFuture&lt;Response&gt; serverResponseCf = service.get(&quot;someKey&quot;);
    serverResponseCf.thenApplyAsync(
      Response response -&gt; {
        String id = response.getId();
        return retrieveDifferentObject(id);
      }
    ).thenAcceptAsync(
       BundledResponse thatDiffObject -&gt; {
         /* Here I need the ID also, that was retrieved in previous stage. */
       }
    ).
... chain goes on
```

This way, you can get both the new data you need AND the id you passed in. There are a couple of ways to do it, but this is pretty much the first thing Java developers reach for nowadays.


  [1]: https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/20/docs/api/java.base/java/lang/Record.html

