# tl;dr

To simply run tests written with JUnit 5, you do *not* need the *…Suite…* tools. Just specify the [aggregate JUnit + Jupiter archetype][1].

```xml
&lt;artifactId&gt;junit-jupiter&lt;/artifactId&gt;
```

If you want to use the Suite features of JUnit, you need to add two more dependencies. Of course, you need at least one test engine such as *Jupiter*.

# Details

The [*JUnit Platform Suite Engine*][2] is for running tests with *any* of many possible [test engines][3], and no one engine in particular. 

## *Jupiter*

[JUnit 5][4] is designed to be a harness for one or more test engines. 

One test engine is provided by the JUnit team, named *Jupiter*. JUnit 5 can run Jupiter-based tests, and JUnit 5 can run tests from other third-party test engines. Jupiter is but one of several test engines compatible with JUnit 5. 

If you just want to run Jupiter tests, the replacement for JUnit 4 tests, you do not need *JUnit Platform Suite Engine*. Instead, just configure your Maven POM to specify the [aggregate JUnit + Jupiter archetype][1].

```xml
&lt;!-- https://mvnrepository.com/artifact/org.junit.jupiter/junit-jupiter --&gt;
&lt;dependency&gt;
    &lt;groupId&gt;org.junit.jupiter&lt;/groupId&gt;
    &lt;artifactId&gt;junit-jupiter&lt;/artifactId&gt;
    &lt;version&gt;5.10.0-RC2&lt;/version&gt;
    &lt;scope&gt;test&lt;/scope&gt;
&lt;/dependency&gt;
```

That archetype brings in three artifacts:

 - [JUnit Jupiter Engine][5] 
 - [JUnit Jupiter API][6]
 - [JUnit Jupiter Params][7]

These in turn bring in artifacts for the JUnit 5 test harness platform.

Here is an example [POM][8], my modified version of the POM from the [*Maven Quickstart Archetype*][9].

```xml
